		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center show-name">
			<h1 class="show-h1">
				Iceland
			</h1>
		</div>
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center show-lesson">
			<h5 class="show-h5">
				Lesson 8
			</h5>
		</div>
			
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<img class="show-flag" src="https://cdn.britannica.com/85/1485-004-94C3DEDA/Flag-Iceland.jpg">
		</div>
		
		<div class='d-flex justify-content-center show-firstquickfacth4'>
			<h4>Capital: Reykjavik</h4>
		</div>
		
		<div class='d-flex justify-content-center show-quickfactsh4'>
			<h4>Population: 360,000</h4>
		</div>
		
		<div class='d-flex justify-content-center show-quickfactsh4'>
			<h4>Gross Domestic Product (GDP): 24 billion dollars</h4>
		</div>
		
		<div class='d-flex justify-content-center show-quickfactsh4'>
			<h4>Gross Domestic Product (GDP) Per Capita: 67,000 dollars</h4>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<hr class="show-hr1">	
		
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1 show-map" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f8/Iceland_in_Europe_%28-rivers_-mini_map%29.svg/1198px-Iceland_in_Europe_%28-rivers_-mini_map%29.svg.png">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Iceland is a Nordic Island country, home to over 360,000 people. Iceland was settled in the 9th century BC by the Vikings. In 1262 Iceland united with Norway becoming a part of the Danish Crown. Iceland stayed with Denmark even after Norway gained its independence. In 1918 Iceland became an independent state of Denmark, and later established themselves as an independent Republic in 1944.
			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Iceland’s climate is somewhat mild considering its location right below the polar circle. It has windy and snowy winters with temperatures between 25-35 degrees (Fahrenheit). Summers are cool and breezy between 45-55 degrees (Fahrenheit). The aurora borealis is visible in the nights during winter. And you can see a midnight sun in the summers!
			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1" src="https://imagesvc.meredithcorp.io/v3/mm/image?url=https%3A%2F%2Fstatic.onecms.io%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2Fsites%2F28%2F2019%2F11%2Fnorthern-lights-kirkjufell-mountain-snaefellsnes-iceland-ICELANDLIGHTS1218.jpg">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
					<em><figcaption>The aurora borealis in Iceland</figcaption></em>
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Iceland is not only a land of ice, but also one of fire with its steamy geysers, hot spring, and fiery volcanoes. In 1875 Iceland suffered a major volcanic eruption that caused a widespread famine which led 20% of the population to leave the country.

			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1" src="https://storage.googleapis.com/afs-prod/media/dec2eb305a304ebabff07f27e9fad001/3000.jpeg">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
					<em><figcaption>The Fagradalsfjall volcano in Iceland eurpted in 2021 after lying dormant for 800 years</figcaption></em>
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Today Iceland is known for its beautiful Blue Lagoon (a giant seawater bathtub) crystal blue ice caves, and beautiful seabirds with multi colored beaks called Puffins.

			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1" src="https://i0.wp.com/files.tripstodiscover.com/files/2016/11/bigstock-blue-lagoon-near-Reykjavik-Ic-83067611-1.jpg?resize=784%2C588">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
					<em><figcaption>Blue Lagoon in Iceland</figcaption></em>
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Iceland’s capital is the city of Reykjavik. People of Iceland speak Icelandic, Nordic, German and English. Their currency is the Icelandic Krona (ISK). Their major industries are fishing and geothermal power.

			</p>
		</div>
	
		
		

		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<h3 class="show-factsh3">
				Two unique facts about Iceland
			</h3>
		</div>
			
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				In Iceland the children are not given last names. Instead they are given first names of their parents, a tradition known as patronymic. For example: if your name is Jack and your father’s name is Larry you will be named Jack Larry-son. For daughters the word do`ttir is applied, for example Jane Larry-do`ttir.
			</p>
		</div>
		
		
	
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Håkarl, is a traditional Icelandic food. It is shark meat that is hung-dried, or buried under ground for several months to cure and is described as 100 times stronger than blue cheese. Yum!
			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1" src="https://www.culinaryschools.org/images/hanging-hakarl.jpg">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
					<em><figcaption>Traditional Icelandic Håkarl</figcaption></em>
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		
		
		
		
